Socket.IO provides a high level of abstraction, allowing you to focus on the logic of your game client while it handles the underlying WebSocket communication. However, if you need to work with raw WebSockets, you can use the built-in WebSocket API in modern browsers, though it will require more manual connection and message handling.

The simplest and highest abstraction client for WebSocket in JavaScript is the WebSocket API, which is included in most modern web browsers. It provides a low-level API for creating WebSocket connections and sending and receiving messages. Here is an example of how to create a WebSocket connection in JavaScript:
```javascript
const socket = new WebSocket('ws://localhost:8080');

socket.addEventListener('open', () => {
  console.log('WebSocket connection established');
});

socket.addEventListener('message', event => {
  console.log('Received message:', event.data);
});

socket.addEventListener('close', event => {
  console.log('WebSocket connection closed:', event.code, event.reason);
});
```

This code creates a WebSocket connection to a server running on localhost at port 8080. When the connection is established, the open event is fired, and a message is logged to the console. When a message is received from the server, the message event is fired, and the message is logged to the console. When the connection is closed, the close event is fired, and the status code and reason are logged to the console.

Of course, you may need to add additional functionality to this basic example depending on the requirements of your game backend. It is also worth noting that there are many WebSocket libraries available for JavaScript that provide higher-level abstractions and additional features, such as automatic reconnection, authentication, and message queueing. You may want to consider using one of these libraries depending on your specific needs.

